    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ad, Ag, Ai-k). Stands exist on the lower foothills bordering inland valleys, where high fire frequencies have impacted the alliance, which is a threatened interior Coast Range saltbush scrub (Holland 1986).</li>
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Ca-d). Stands occur mostly in alkaline basins and along washes and stream channels. Small stands in Anza-Borrego Desert State Park also favor the steep colluvial slopes in alkaline badlands called mud hills.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ag, Aq, Av-z). Stands occur on the edges of the southern San Joaquin Valley, where agriculture development and high fire frequencies have destroyed or altered the extent and composition of the alliance. Some stands have colorful, diverse annual flower displays in wet years.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa-p). Stands occur throughout the section, especially in the western subsections where they cover thousands of hectares (Keeler-Wolf 2007b, Thomas et al. 2004). Some stands have colorful, diverse annual flower displays and very high cover of non-native grasses in wet years.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fd-e). Stands occur in the southern subsections. These have been diminished by grazing, development, and altered fire regimes.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sonoran Desert</b> (322Ba-e). Small stands occupy alkaline basins, including in the Cadiz-Vidal and Chuckwalla valleys (Evens and Hartman 2007); they also occur along washes and stream channels.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fa-f). Stands occur mostly in alkaline basins; they also occur along washes and stream channels in the Eureka, Owens, and Saline valleys (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Atriplex polycarpa </i>is palatable to livestock, and many stands have a history of heavy grazing. Losses due to agriculture development are high in the Central Valley and surrounding foothills. Threatened <i>A. polycarpa </i>types in this region (Holland 1986) need more study and protection. Managers are concerned that current fire regimes are reducing the alliance’s extent. In arid areas at low elevations, fire was less important than at upper elevations (Desert Workshop 2000). Protection from fire is necessary in the western Mojave Desert, San Joaquin Valley, and surrounding foothills. The natural disturbance cycle over much of its range also includes flooding events. </div>
</div>

    

    

